  "advice": "Hey Tom, great work on the recent races! You're building a fantastic foundation for NYC.\n\n### **Fitness Assessment**\nYou're demonstrating excellent aerobic fitness for this base-building phase. Your Newport Half Marathon (13.31mi @ 8:35/mi | HR 151bpm, Z2) was a very strong performance, maintaining a solid Z2 pace for the entire distance. This suggests your current Riegel marathon prediction of 4:12:36 might be conservative, as you ran your half significantly faster than the predicted pace. Your Cherry Blossom 10 Mile (10.19mi @ 8:41/mi | HR 156bpm, Z3) also shows you can push when needed. Crucially, your easy runs are consistently in Z2 (e.g., 3.01mi @ 10:20/mi | HR 145bpm, Z2), indicating great control and understanding of easy effort.\n\n### **This Week's Focus**\nThe goal this week is active recovery from your recent race efforts and continued aerobic base building.\n*   **Easy Runs (Z2):** Target a pace of **9:45 - 10:30/mi**, ensuring your heart rate stays comfortably in Z2 (124-154 bpm). Prioritize effort over pace, especially with the upcoming weather.\n*   **Long Run:** Aim for **8-10 miles** at an easy Z2 pace. Focus on consistent effort rather than pushing distance after the half marathon.\n*   **Weather Adaptation:** Brace for significant rain and wind this weekend and early next week. Dress appropriately (waterproof outer layers, hat), watch your footing, and be prepared to adjust your pace if conditions are challenging.\n*   **Sample Schedule (adjust as needed):**\n    *   **Fri, Apr 24:** 3.01mi @ 10:20/mi (completed)\n    *   **Sat, Apr 25 (Rain/Wind):** 4-5 miles Easy (Z2)\n    *   **Sun, Apr 26 (Rain/Wind):** 8-10 miles Long Run (Z2)\n    *   **Mon, Apr 27:** Rest or light cross-train\n    *   **Tue, Apr 28:** 3-4 miles Easy (Z2)\n    *   **Wed, Apr 29 (Drizzle):** 4-5 miles Easy (Z2)\n    *   **Thu, Apr 30 (Drizzle):** Rest or light cross-train\n\n### **Key Priorities**\n*   **Active Recovery:** Allow your body to fully absorb the recent race efforts. All runs should feel easy and controlled.\n*   **Consistent Aerobic Base:** Maintain regular, easy Z2 runs to continue building your endurance foundation.\n*   **Smart Weather Running:** Adapt to the wet and windy conditions by dressing appropriately and focusing on safe, controlled efforts.\n\n### **Watch Out For**\n*   **Pace Creep:** After strong race performances, there can be a natural tendency to push easy runs too hard. Stick strictly to Z2 for all non-race efforts this week to ensure proper recovery.\n*   **Over-scheduling:** Ensure adequate rest days, especially coming off two races. Listen to your body and don't hesitate to swap a run for cross-training or an extra rest day if you feel fatigued.\n*   **Weather-related hazards:** Be extra mindful of slippery surfaces, reduced visibility, and potential gusts of wind during your runs.\n\n### **Upcoming Milestones**\n*   **Next 2-3 Weeks:** We'll continue to gradually build your weekly mileage and long run distance, ensuring all efforts remain comfortably in Z2.\n*   **Strides Introduction:** We'll soon introduce 4-6 x 20-30 second strides at the end of 1-2 easy runs per week. This helps maintain leg speed without adding significant stress.\n*   **Building Foundation:** We have about 9 weeks left in this base-building phase before the official training plan starts on July 1st. The focus will remain on consistent, easy mileage to prepare your body for the increased demands ahead."
